33
00:01:13,980 --> 00:01:18,440
And Git has become kind of the
de facto tool in this space.

34
00:01:18,440 --> 00:01:23,550
So Git, G-I-T, that is
the underlying software.

35
00:01:23,550 --> 00:01:25,460
It is a version control
system, that would

36
00:01:25,460 --> 00:01:27,500
be the formal definition of it.

37
00:01:27,500 --> 00:01:29,450
Version control in
the sense that, hey, I

38
00:01:29,450 --> 00:01:31,250
have one version of the code.

39
00:01:31,250 --> 00:01:34,190
I write my initial code, it
goes up there on the website,

40
00:01:34,190 --> 00:01:36,770
or goes live wherever
it is, and then

41
00:01:36,770 --> 00:01:38,810
I might make a change
to it, therefore, there

42
00:01:38,810 --> 00:01:40,290
is a new version of it.

43
00:01:40,290 --> 00:01:41,780
Similarly, I might
have a coworker

44
00:01:41,780 --> 00:01:44,370
that makes a change to it, that
is a different version of it.

45
00:01:44,370 --> 00:01:46,010
So Git is software
that allows us

46
00:01:46,010 --> 00:01:48,920
to manage kind of the
interaction of these two things.

47
00:01:48,920 --> 00:01:51,600
How do we make sure that they
work together effectively?

48
00:01:51,600 --> 00:01:53,300
How do we make
sure that we don't

49
00:01:53,300 --> 00:01:54,810
overwrite each other's work?

50
00:01:54,810 --> 00:01:57,740
And if we need to roll back
to previous code, where

51
00:01:57,740 --> 00:02:00,738
