username and my user email.

173
00:07:35,390 --> 00:07:37,230
So the username
is arbitrary here.

174
00:07:37,230 --> 00:07:40,220
It's not even saying necessarily
it's your GitHub username.

175
00:07:40,220 --> 00:07:41,690
We're not to GitHub yet, right?

176
00:07:41,690 --> 00:07:43,820
We're just focusing
on Git right now.

177
00:07:43,820 --> 00:07:47,710
So before GitHub even existed,
Git was already there, right?

178
00:07:47,710 --> 00:07:49,690
So this is already an
option to collaborate

179
00:07:49,690 --> 00:07:51,250
with other developers.

180
00:07:51,250 --> 00:07:53,630
You can check to see
configurations here.

181
00:07:53,630 --> 00:07:56,970
Just doing git config --list.

182
00:07:56,970 --> 00:08:00,870
And now we're set up to
create our first repository.

183
00:08:00,870 --> 00:08:02,860
So I'm going to do mkdir.

184
00:08:02,860 --> 00:08:04,680
Remember, that's make directory.

185
00:08:04,680 --> 00:08:06,915
And it will be called
my-git-project.

186
00:08:09,550 --> 00:08:14,840
Then I'll cd into there,
so cd into my-git-project.

187
00:08:14,840 --> 00:08:18,420
And then to initialize
it as a Git repository,

188
00:08:18,420 --> 00:08:20,750
basically saying to
tell Git that, hey, you

189
00:08:20,750 --> 00:08:23,930
should start monitoring this
repository for any changes,

190
00:08:23,930 --> 00:08:30,380
we'll call it git init,
for initialize, -b main,

191
00:08:30,380 --> 00:08:33,500
where the -b main
sets the default

192
00:08:33,500 --> 00:08:35,850
branch to the main branch.

193
00:08:35,850 --> 00:08:37,799
And we'll talk about
branching in a second.

194
00:08:37,799 --> 00:08:39,424
But the way to think
about it right now

195
00:08:39,424 --> 00:08:41,150
is just that the
branch just defines

196
00:08:41,150 --> 00:08:44,370
kind of what thread of work am
I doing, what am I building.

197
00:08:44,370 --> 00:08:47,690
And the default is to
have a main branch that

198
00:08:47,690 --> 00:08:50,820
is kind of the live or working
version of the application,

199
00:08:50,820 --> 00:08:51,980
ideally.

200
00:08:51,980 --> 00:08:54,200
That way, anything
new that's developed

201
00:08:54,200 --> 00:08:56,490
has to get merged
into the main branch.

202
00:08:56,490 --> 00:08:58,550
But again, we'll
come back to that.

203
00:08:58,550 --> 00:09:02,070
So first, let's actually
just create a file in here.

204
00:09:02,070 --> 00:09:05,130
So I'll do nano, and
we'll call the file,

205
00:09:05,130 --> 00:09:06,530
we'll just make a readme.

206
00:09:06,530 --> 00:09:09,950
And we'll make it a
markdown file, so .md.

207
00:09:09,950 --> 00:09:12,270
And a markdown file, if
you're not familiar with that,

208
00:09:12,270 --> 00:09:17,070
is just a special file type that
is often used for text files.

209
00:09:17,070 --> 00:09:20,480
And in this case, you can
use special characters,

210
00:09:20,480 --> 00:09:23,730
like this hash mark
here, we'll do a header.

211
00:09:23,730 --> 00:09:28,230
So we're just making the
title of this my-git-project.

212
00:09:28,230 --> 00:09:29,435
So we'll save that.

213
00:09:32,100 --> 00:09:36,780
And now we have to go through
what I kind of treat as the--

214
00:09:36,780 --> 00:09:41,310
or part of the default loop
for tracking changes or pushing

215
00:09:41,310 --> 00:09:43,260
changes to your repository.

216
00:09:43,260 --> 00:09:46,210
So first thing I usually
do is I run git status.

217
00:09:46,210 --> 00:09:48,720
That tells me what
branch I'm on,

218
00:09:48,720 --> 00:09:52,600
do I have any commits that
have been submitted yet,

219
00:09:52,600 --> 00:09:56,550
and importantly, are there any
untracked files or changes will

220
00:09:56,550 --> 00:09:59,181
also show up show up here too.

221
00:09:59,181 --> 00:10:02,820
To add something to a
track-- to be a tracked file,

222
00:10:02,820 --> 00:10:07,080
we run git add, and
you can either specify

223
00:10:07,080 --> 00:10:08,550
the specific files name.

224
00:10:08,550 --> 00:10:10,330
Or if you've made
a bunch of changes,

225
00:10:10,330 --> 00:10:13,590
there's a bunch of new files, a
shortcut is to just say git add

226
00:10:13,590 --> 00:10:16,500
and then period, and that'll
add everything that's untracked

227
00:10:16,500 --> 00:10:19,410
or any new changes to
just being tracked.

228
00:10:19,410 --> 00:10:23,100
Or-- yeah, to being monitored.

229
00:10:23,100 --> 00:10:25,890
So now, after I've run
the git add everything,

230
00:10:25,890 --> 00:10:27,930
and I run git status,
you can see now

231
00:10:27,930 --> 00:10:30,060
that we have no
commits still, but we

232
00:10:30,060 --> 00:10:36,280
have some changes that are
kind of staged to be committed.

233
00:10:36,280 --> 00:10:42,040
And then to commit it, we
just run git commit /m.

234
00:10:42,040 --> 00:10:44,080
And we'll just say
initial commit,

235
00:10:44,080 --> 00:10:46,930
because this is
our first commit.

236
00:10:46,930 --> 00:10:49,870
So the way to think about
this is what we've done so far

237
00:10:49,870 --> 00:10:52,180
is we've said, hey,
we've made some change.

238
00:10:52,180 --> 00:10:55,610
We need to be watching this
change, monitoring this change.

239
00:10:55,610 --> 00:10:57,830
And now I'm committing
this change to saying,

240
00:10:57,830 --> 00:11:01,070
hey, this is a new change
that has been made.

241
00:11:01,070 --> 00:11:03,860
But again, recognize that this
is all just still isolated

242
00:11:03,860 --> 00:11:05,690
to my local repository.

243
00:11:05,690 --> 00:11:08,780
Or this is only on this
machine, on this EC2 instance.

244
00:11:08,780 --> 00:11:11,210
It's not accessible
anywhere else.

245
00:11:11,210 --> 00:11:13,220
Now what we want to
do is push that up

246
00:11:13,220 --> 00:11:14,910
to our remote repository.

247
00:11:14,910 --> 00:11:17,520
Our remote repository
is going to be GitHub.

248
00:11:17,520 --> 00:11:20,640
We're going to use GitHub as the
place to push all our code to.

249
00:11:20,640 --> 00:11:23,710
So that way anybody
can interact with it.

250
00:11:23,710 --> 00:11:25,930
So one of the first
things you need to do

251
00:11:25,930 --> 00:11:28,720
is come to github.com and
just create an account

252
00:11:28,720 --> 00:11:30,420
if you don't already have one.

253
00:11:30,420 --> 00:11:33,200
If you do have one,
just log in to it.

254
00:11:33,200 --> 00:11:36,190
And so, yeah, feel free to pause
it if you're in that moment

255
00:11:36,190 --> 00:11:41,812
right now, just kind of waiting
for that to create your account.

256
00:11:41,812 --> 00:11:43,520
Once you've created
your account, though,

257
00:11:43,520 --> 00:11:45,603
what I want you to do is
click on your little icon

258
00:11:45,603 --> 00:11:50,080
on the top right here and
scroll down, click Settings.

259
00:11:50,080 --> 00:11:52,690
And then if you scroll to
the very bottom of settings

260
00:11:52,690 --> 00:11:56,530
here and click
developer settings,

261
00:11:56,530 --> 00:12:01,650
you can click Personal access
tokens, Tokens classic.

262
00:12:01,650 --> 00:12:04,710
And then, we're going to
generate a new token up here

263
00:12:04,710 --> 00:12:08,580
on the top right, and
Generate new token classic.

264
00:12:08,580 --> 00:12:12,900
So personal access tokens are
basically kind of secure way

265
00:12:12,900 --> 00:12:17,260
to interact with our repository
from a remote machine.

266
00:12:17,260 --> 00:12:19,170
Basically, it's kind
of like our secret keys

267
00:12:19,170 --> 00:12:20,950
that we've had before
where it says, hey,

268
00:12:20,950 --> 00:12:24,120
I have to have this secret
key to be able to interact

269
00:12:24,120 --> 00:12:25,420
with the remote repository.

270
00:12:25,420 --> 00:12:27,990
If you don't have one of these,
you won't be able to do it.

271
00:12:27,990 --> 00:12:30,580
So we can call us
whatever we want to.

272
00:12:30,580 --> 00:12:33,060
I'll call mine
temporarytoken, because I'm

273
00:12:33,060 --> 00:12:35,880
going to delete it
basically immediately.

274
00:12:35,880 --> 00:12:38,705
I'm going to set the
expiration for seven days.

275
00:12:38,705 --> 00:12:40,830
But note that, again, the
expiration is, treat this

276
00:12:40,830 --> 00:12:43,620
as another kind of
security protocol,

277
00:12:43,620 --> 00:12:47,130
is to say that I will
set a amount of time

278
00:12:47,130 --> 00:12:51,720
that I want this token
to be viable for.

279
00:12:51,720 --> 00:12:53,910
And then, after
that point, it is

280
00:12:53,910 --> 00:12:56,410
going to be basically just
an expired token, right?

281
00:12:56,410 --> 00:12:59,820
I won't be able to
use it for validation

282
00:12:59,820 --> 00:13:02,670
of my personal profile.

283
00:13:02,670 --> 00:13:04,103
The reason we do
this is that it's

284
00:13:04,103 --> 00:13:05,770
kind of the same as
changing a password.

285
00:13:05,770 --> 00:13:08,320
After a certain amount of
time, just from a security

286
00:13:08,320 --> 00:13:09,850
perspective, it's
probably better

287
00:13:09,850 --> 00:13:11,947
to just revoke
that token's access

288
00:13:11,947 --> 00:13:13,780
and then create a new
one, just to make sure

289
00:13:13,780 --> 00:13:15,010
that you're staying
relevant with it

290
00:13:15,010 --> 00:13:16,450
and you don't have anything
that's kind of lingering

291
00:13:16,450 --> 00:13:17,990
around unnecessarily.

292
00:13:17,990 --> 00:13:20,990
So 7 days, 30 days, 60 days, 90
days, whatever you want to do.

293
00:13:20,990 --> 00:13:22,280
We're just doing this for now.

294
00:13:22,280 --> 00:13:23,470
And you'll have
assignments where

295
00:13:23,470 --> 00:13:25,137
you'll need to push
to GitHub, so you're

296
00:13:25,137 --> 00:13:26,590
welcome to do it for longer.

297
00:13:26,590 --> 00:13:27,980
But again, no expiration.

298
00:13:27,980 --> 00:13:29,563
It's going to probably
flag you, yeah.

299
00:13:29,563 --> 00:13:31,820
And say, hey, this isn't
very secure to do this.

300
00:13:31,820 --> 00:13:33,900
So you probably
shouldn't do that.

301
00:13:33,900 --> 00:13:34,540
For right now.

302
00:13:34,540 --> 00:13:36,150
I'm going to set mine to 7.

303
00:13:36,150 --> 00:13:37,950
And then you need to
basically just specify

304
00:13:37,950 --> 00:13:40,000
what it has access to.

305
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:41,670
And for right now,
we really just need

306
00:13:41,670 --> 00:13:44,650
to have access over
our repositories.

307
00:13:44,650 --> 00:13:47,280
So I'll just give it
permissions to the repos.

308
00:13:47,280 --> 00:13:51,210
And then everything else, I'm
just going to leave blank.

309
00:13:51,210 --> 00:13:53,850
And then click Generate token.

310
00:13:53,850 --> 00:13:57,120
Now on this page,
you'll see this

311
00:13:57,120 --> 00:13:59,560
is your secret token, your
personal access token.

312
00:13:59,560 --> 00:14:01,060
Again, this is a private thing.

313
00:14:01,060 --> 00:14:03,720
Obviously, mine, you
guys can see it here.

314
00:14:03,720 --> 00:14:05,380
So that's not very secure.

315
00:14:05,380 --> 00:14:07,117
But I'm obviously
also, first off,

316
00:14:07,117 --> 00:14:08,950
going to delete this
once I'm done using it.

317
00:14:08,950 --> 00:14:10,710
So it won't even
be viable anymore.

318
00:14:10,710 --> 00:14:12,550
And also, in seven
days, no matter what,

319
00:14:12,550 --> 00:14:15,300
the access, the permissions to
this are going to be revoked.

320
00:14:15,300 --> 00:14:18,090
But you need to make sure
to copy this and store it

321
00:14:18,090 --> 00:14:19,360
somewhere secure.

322
00:14:19,360 --> 00:14:21,435
So wherever that
works for you, we're

323
00:14:21,435 --> 00:14:22,810
going to need it
throughout this.

324
00:14:22,810 --> 00:14:26,550
So I'm putting it in a little
notepad for myself temporarily,

325
00:14:26,550 --> 00:14:28,320
while I'm using it.

326
00:14:28,320 --> 00:14:32,050
But there are a whole suite of
more secure ways to do that.

327
00:14:32,050 --> 00:14:34,540
But for now, again,
perfectly fine,

328
00:14:34,540 --> 00:14:38,220
just put it in a little
notepad for yourself to access.

329
00:14:38,220 --> 00:14:40,590
So we have that now.

330
00:14:40,590 --> 00:14:43,230
So let's come back over and
click on the little icon

331
00:14:43,230 --> 00:14:46,780
up here, the octocat
icon for GitHub.

332
00:14:46,780 --> 00:14:49,750
And then we're going to
create a new repository.

333
00:14:49,750 --> 00:14:52,300
And we're just going to name
this repository exactly what we

334
00:14:52,300 --> 00:14:58,850
named our other-- or our local
repository, my-git-project.

335
00:14:58,850 --> 00:15:02,820
And note that it needs to be
unique within your account.

336
00:15:02,820 --> 00:15:05,600
So if it's-- it doesn't
have to be unique globally,

337
00:15:05,600 --> 00:15:08,190
kind of like our S3 buckets do.

338
00:15:08,190 --> 00:15:11,150
It just needs to be
unique within our account.

339
00:15:11,150 --> 00:15:13,350
You can add a
description if you want.

340
00:15:13,350 --> 00:15:18,080
You can specify whether your
repository is public or private.

341
00:15:18,080 --> 00:15:21,740
Public is good if you want
to show this off to others.

342
00:15:21,740 --> 00:15:23,450
Or, for example,
like when you guys

343
00:15:23,450 --> 00:15:26,780
are going to need to send me
links to your repositories

344
00:15:26,780 --> 00:15:28,440
to show me that
you completed work.

345
00:15:28,440 --> 00:15:29,990
Easiest thing to do would
be to make it public,

346
00:15:29,990 --> 00:15:31,865
so you don't have to
add me as a collaborator

347
00:15:31,865 --> 00:15:33,380
or anything like that.

348
00:15:33,380 --> 00:15:35,120
Though, note you
can still choose who

349
00:15:35,120 --> 00:15:36,585
actually can commit code to it.

350
00:15:36,585 --> 00:15:38,210
So it's not saying
I'm making it public

351
00:15:38,210 --> 00:15:39,810
and anybody can change my code.

352
00:15:39,810 --> 00:15:42,920
It's just saying it's
visible publicly.

353
00:15:42,920 --> 00:15:45,680
And then private
is you basically

354
00:15:45,680 --> 00:15:49,210
choose who can see and
commit to this repository.

355
00:15:49,210 --> 00:15:51,487
So I'll just leave mine
as private for now.

356
00:15:51,487 --> 00:15:54,070
So I don't have just a million
of these private repositories--

357
00:15:54,070 --> 00:15:56,840
or default repositories created.

358
00:15:56,840 --> 00:15:58,680
But leave everything
else here blank.

359
00:15:58,680 --> 00:16:00,430
I'll explain what
these are, but we

360
00:16:00,430 --> 00:16:02,033
don't want to change
anything here,

361
00:16:02,033 --> 00:16:03,700
because we're pushing
all of our changes

362
00:16:03,700 --> 00:16:05,270
from our local repository.

363
00:16:05,270 --> 00:16:07,610
So don't add any of
these things here.

364
00:16:07,610 --> 00:16:09,845
But in case you're
curious, the readme

365
00:16:09,845 --> 00:16:11,470
file, we'll we just
created one, right?

366
00:16:11,470 --> 00:16:13,070
We created one our
local repository.

367
00:16:13,070 --> 00:16:14,510
So that's why we don't need one.

368
00:16:14,510 --> 00:16:17,320
This is where you typically
will see the description of what

369
00:16:17,320 --> 00:16:18,680
the project does.

370
00:16:18,680 --> 00:16:20,023
So that's kind of a default one.

371
00:16:20,023 --> 00:16:21,940
And that's why they have
it as an option here.

372
00:16:21,940 --> 00:16:25,430
We'll talk about gitignores
in a future lecture,

373
00:16:25,430 --> 00:16:28,330
but the short version
of it is that gitignore

374
00:16:28,330 --> 00:16:31,420
is a special file that
says, hey, I maybe

375
00:16:31,420 --> 00:16:34,490
want to ignore specific file
types within my repository.

376
00:16:34,490 --> 00:16:37,040
Like never push those
up to my remote.

377
00:16:37,040 --> 00:16:40,090
So if, for example, I
had a public repository

378
00:16:40,090 --> 00:16:42,168
for some sort of
application I built

379
00:16:42,168 --> 00:16:43,710
and I want it to be
visible to others

380
00:16:43,710 --> 00:16:47,060
so they could build off of it or
kind of see the work I've done,

381
00:16:47,060 --> 00:16:51,800
but it requires that I
have some secret tokens

382
00:16:51,800 --> 00:16:54,300
to launch the website
on my local machine.

383
00:16:54,300 --> 00:16:58,580
I can add my secret tokens
file to the gitignore

384
00:16:58,580 --> 00:17:01,650
and say, hey, even though
this is in that repository,

385
00:17:01,650 --> 00:17:05,030
never track it, never
push it to the repository.

386
00:17:05,030 --> 00:17:07,140
And then finally is the license.

387
00:17:07,140 --> 00:17:09,500
And this is basically
where you can

388
00:17:09,500 --> 00:17:11,869
define who has what sort
of legal permissions

389
00:17:11,869 --> 00:17:14,190
to interact with your code.

390
00:17:14,190 --> 00:17:16,819
Even though oftentimes,
and actually many of these

391
00:17:16,819 --> 00:17:18,980
are open source licenses
in the sense that they

392
00:17:18,980 --> 00:17:22,010
say anybody can use this
code, certain licenses

393
00:17:22,010 --> 00:17:23,880
will say, hey, you
can use this code,

394
00:17:23,880 --> 00:17:26,280
but just not for
commercial purposes.

395
00:17:26,280 --> 00:17:27,980
So this will be
relevant to you as you

396
00:17:27,980 --> 00:17:29,630
start to build
products and companies,

397
00:17:29,630 --> 00:17:30,630
and all sorts of things.

398
00:17:30,630 --> 00:17:33,530
But for right now, that's
not a big deal for us.

399
00:17:33,530 --> 00:17:36,890
So we'll click
Create repository.

400
00:17:36,890 --> 00:17:38,610
And now we'll be
brought to this page.

401
00:17:38,610 --> 00:17:40,920
So our repository
has been created.

402
00:17:40,920 --> 00:17:42,930
We haven't put
anything in it yet,

403
00:17:42,930 --> 00:17:45,320
but we have all
that set up there.

404
00:17:45,320 --> 00:17:48,740
So now I'll slide this over
out the way for a little bit

405
00:17:48,740 --> 00:17:52,100
so we can type again.

406
00:17:52,100 --> 00:17:55,340
And so now we want to
push our local code up

407
00:17:55,340 --> 00:17:57,090
to our remote repository.

408
00:17:57,090 --> 00:17:59,370
So first thing I need
to do is come down here.

409
00:17:59,370 --> 00:18:02,090
You'll see there's this line
here that gives us some tips,

410
00:18:02,090 --> 00:18:03,620
actually, if we want to
create a new repository,

411
00:18:03,620 --> 00:18:05,340
or if we want to
push an existing one.

412
00:18:05,340 --> 00:18:07,070
We want to push an
existing one. so we'll

413
00:18:07,070 --> 00:18:14,700
do copy this top line that
says git remote add origin,

414
00:18:14,700 --> 00:18:16,470
and then it has a URL.

415
00:18:16,470 --> 00:18:20,510
So that's saying, hey, we're
adding a remote repository.

416
00:18:20,510 --> 00:18:24,110
And origin is just the standard
name for remote repository.

417
00:18:24,110 --> 00:18:30,030
And it is going to be
pushing to this URL here,

418
00:18:30,030 --> 00:18:32,762
so github.com/sharadkj/mid
git project.git.

419
00:18:35,750 --> 00:18:37,520
And so that's
saying, hey, now we

420
00:18:37,520 --> 00:18:41,630
have our local repository that
has a remote connection that

421
00:18:41,630 --> 00:18:43,280
goes out to this
location, right,

422
00:18:43,280 --> 00:18:46,040
to this specific
remote repository.

423
00:18:46,040 --> 00:18:48,800
So hit Enter and it shouldn't
say anything if it worked.

424
00:18:48,800 --> 00:18:53,140
And then, last step here,
we have-- if you remember,

425
00:18:53,140 --> 00:18:56,490
if we do git status,
we have some--

426
00:18:56,490 --> 00:18:59,800
or better statement, we
have committed our changes.

427
00:18:59,800 --> 00:19:03,780
We have some initial--

428
00:19:03,780 --> 00:19:05,530
we have initial file in there.

429
00:19:05,530 --> 00:19:08,350
And so now we want to push this
up to our remote repository.

430
00:19:08,350 --> 00:19:16,150
So we'll run git
push -u origin main.

431
00:19:16,150 --> 00:19:20,320
And so this just sets the-- the
u sets the upstream reference

432
00:19:20,320 --> 00:19:23,560
basically for any sort of future
pushes or pulls we're doing.

433
00:19:23,560 --> 00:19:26,710
So we're saying git
push u origin main.

434
00:19:26,710 --> 00:19:29,770
Then it's going to say,
give me your username.

435
00:19:29,770 --> 00:19:31,270
And then, for the
password, we're

436
00:19:31,270 --> 00:19:33,400
not going to put
our GitHub password,

437
00:19:33,400 --> 00:19:35,800
we're going to paste that
personal access token that we

438
00:19:35,800 --> 00:19:38,120
created and stored into a file.

439
00:19:38,120 --> 00:19:39,680
So literally, just
copy and paste.

440
00:19:39,680 --> 00:19:41,290
That's all I did
there, is Control-C

441
00:19:41,290 --> 00:19:44,110
and Control-V. It doesn't show
anything when you paste it

442
00:19:44,110 --> 00:19:45,740
there, so don't panic.

443
00:19:45,740 --> 00:19:48,850
But if it showed like this
correctly or if it shows

444
00:19:48,850 --> 00:19:51,370
basically branch main setup
to track remote manage main

445
00:19:51,370 --> 00:19:55,030
from origin, all that good
stuff, then you're great.

446
00:19:55,030 --> 00:19:57,740
If it threw an error of
any sort, easy enough.

447
00:19:57,740 --> 00:20:00,130
Just rerun this command,
put in your username,

448
00:20:00,130 --> 00:20:04,390
and put in the personal
access token as your password.

449
00:20:04,390 --> 00:20:08,020
Now, if we come back over
here to our remote repository

450
00:20:08,020 --> 00:20:11,960
and hit Refresh,
we see that we have

451
00:20:11,960 --> 00:20:15,330
now a file, an initial
commit for that file.

452
00:20:15,330 --> 00:20:20,910
That initial commit is the
readme that we created.

453
00:20:20,910 --> 00:20:24,980
And we can see that it was 9
minutes ago that I pushed that,

454
00:20:24,980 --> 00:20:26,763
or that I made that
initial commit.

455
00:20:26,763 --> 00:20:28,430
It wasn't 9 minutes
ago that I pushed it

456
00:20:28,430 --> 00:20:29,730
to the remote repository.

457
00:20:29,730 --> 00:20:33,350
It was just 9 minutes ago
that I made that commit.

458
00:20:33,350 --> 00:20:35,360
And so now you have a--

459
00:20:35,360 --> 00:20:38,930
you've kind of seen the
workflow of making changes

460
00:20:38,930 --> 00:20:40,730
to a Git repository.

461
00:20:40,730 --> 00:20:42,810
The standard approach
is to say, hey, well,

462
00:20:42,810 --> 00:20:46,260
maybe I want to add some
more text to my file here,

463
00:20:46,260 --> 00:20:47,930
and this file could
be anything, right?

464
00:20:47,930 --> 00:20:48,990
In our case, it's a readme.

465
00:20:48,990 --> 00:20:50,657
But this could just
be your regular code

466
00:20:50,657 --> 00:20:53,600
for your website, your
application, whatever it is.

467
00:20:53,600 --> 00:20:57,740
So if I want to make a change,
maybe I say, OK, great,

468
00:20:57,740 --> 00:21:02,520
Sharad is the coolest.

469
00:21:02,520 --> 00:21:04,415
And that is going
to make it bold.

470
00:21:07,540 --> 00:21:09,490
And then we'll
save those changes.

471
00:21:09,490 --> 00:21:11,740
And if we do git
status again, you'll

472
00:21:11,740 --> 00:21:14,030
see, OK, well, I modified this.

473
00:21:14,030 --> 00:21:16,750
So I need to run git
add, and even tells you

474
00:21:16,750 --> 00:21:19,090
that, use git add.

475
00:21:19,090 --> 00:21:21,100
I'm going to add everything.

476
00:21:21,100 --> 00:21:25,540
And then I'll do git
commit slash m, which

477
00:21:25,540 --> 00:21:28,090
is how I can pass a message
along with the commit.

478
00:21:28,090 --> 00:21:37,390
And I'll say, added important
details to the readme.

479
00:21:37,390 --> 00:21:39,340
And again, this message
is just for reference

480
00:21:39,340 --> 00:21:40,630
for other developers
that are working,

481
00:21:40,630 --> 00:21:42,672
and they're like, oh, hey,
what did they do here?

482
00:21:42,672 --> 00:21:45,490
I can see very easily
from this description.

483
00:21:45,490 --> 00:21:53,750
So git add, git commit, and then
we'll run our git push origin

484
00:21:53,750 --> 00:21:58,250
main, and then sharadkj.

485
00:21:58,250 --> 00:22:03,340
And then I'll copy and paste
my personal access token.

486
00:22:03,340 --> 00:22:06,850
And then I'll come over
here and I'll hit Refresh.

487
00:22:06,850 --> 00:22:08,190
And boom, there you go.

488
00:22:08,190 --> 00:22:09,880
Sharad is the coolest.

489
